t citizens are faced with in a self-governing democracy, Eric Beerbohm proposes institutional remedies for dealing with them. Beerbohm questions prevailing theories of democracy for failing to account for our dual position as both citizens and subjects. Showing that the obligation to participate in the democratic process is even greater when we risk serving as accomplices to wrongdoing, Beerbohm argues for a distinctive division of labor between citizens and their representatives that charges lawmakers with the responsibility of incorporating their constituents' moral principles into their reasoning about policy. Grappling with the practical issues of democratic decision making, In Our Name engages with political science, law, and psychology to envision mechanisms for citizens seeking to avoid democratic complicity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aDemocracyxMoral and ethical aspects. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aJohn Rawls.  aJustice as Fairness.  aagency.  aassociative accounts.  aauthority.  abelief.  acitizens.  acitizenship.  acoauthors.  acognitive biases.  acognitive burden.  acognitive partisanship.  acomplicity.  acosubjects.  adecision making.  adelegation.  adeliberation.  adeliberative democracy.  ademocracy.  ademocratic institutions.  ademocratic labor.  ademocratic state.  ademocratic theory.  adistributive justice.  aelections.  aepistemic virtues.  aethics.  agovernment.  aheuristics.  ainjustice.  ajudicial mechanisms.  ajudicial review.  ajustice.  alawmaking.  amacrodemocratic theory.  amarginality.  amicrodemocratic theory.  amoral obligations.  amoral value.  amorality.  anonideal democratic theory.  aparticipation.  aparticipatory accounts.  apatriotism.  apeer principle.  aphilosopher-citizens. 